Problem 1: ggplot

Question 1

Consider the following code. Using your own words, explain why the points are not green? (1 point)

require(ggplot2)
## Loading required package: ggplot2
ggplot(data = airquality) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = Wind, y = Ozone, color = "green"))
## Warning: Removed 37 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

The points are not green because the function recognizes color as a variable equals to "green", which has the same property as x = Wind and y = Ozone. If we really want to change the color to green, we need to add color="green" outside the aes() function. The correct code is shown as following:

ggplot(data = airquality) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = Wind, y = Ozone), color = "green")
## Warning: Removed 37 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

Question 2

Map a continuous variable to color, size, and shape. In words, explain why these aesthetics behave differently for categorical vs.continuous variables. (1 point)

head(airquality, 1)
##   Ozone Solar.R Wind Temp Month Day
## 1    41     190  7.4   67     5   1
# We first map a continuous variables to color, size, and shape
ggplot(data = airquality) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = Wind, y = Ozone, 
                           color = Month, 
                           size = Day))
## Warning: Removed 37 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

# We first plot the categorical variables to color, size, and shape
ggplot(data = airquality) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = Wind, y = Ozone, 
                           color = as.factor(Month), 
                           size = as.factor(Day)))
## Warning: Using size for a discrete variable is not advised.
## Removed 37 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

As we can see from above, when mapping continuous variables, there will have scales on the right side. However, when mapping categorical variables, the right side may not show scales. Instead, it will show the elements in each categorical variable.

The difference exists because continuous variables are mainly numbers, which we can do a lot of calculation on it, but categorical variables are mainly characters, we can only few analysis on it.

Question 3

In words, explain what happens if you map the same variable to multiple aesthetics? (1 point)

ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, 
                           color = cyl, 
                           size = cyl))

Take the plot above as an example, the two aesthetics color and size are assigned to cyl. We can see that both of these aesthetics are applied to the variable. When cyl is 4, the points are small and the color is very dark, and when cyl is 8, the points are big and the color is very light.

Question 4

What happens if you map an aesthetic to something other than a variable name, like aes(colour = Temp < 70)? Note, youll also need to specify x and y (2 points)

ggplot(data = airquality) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = Wind, y = Ozone, colour = Temp < 70))
## Warning: Removed 37 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

When we add aes(colour = Temp < 70) into aesthetics, it will help us identify the points that have Temp lower than 70 and higher than or equal to 70 by two different colors. In the plot above, it the point has Temp lower than 70, it is shown as red, and if the point has Temp higher or equal to 70, it is shown as blue.

Problem 2: Simulation study

Suppose that \(X_1, ...,X_n\) are independent and identically distributed (iid) binomial random variables such that \[P(X_i=x|k,p)=\binom{k}{x}p^x(1-p)^{k-x},~x=0,1,...,k\] for all \(i=1,...,n\). Assume that both \(k\) and \(p\) are unknown and use the method of moments to obtain point estimators of both parameters. This somewhat unusual application of the binomial model has been used to estimate crime rates for crimes that are known to have many unreported occurrences. For such a crime, both the true reporting rate, \(p\), and the total number of occurrences, \(k\), are unknown. Equating the first two sample moments to those of the population yields the system of equations \[\bar{X}=kp~~and~~\frac{1}{n}\Sigma_{i=1}^{n}X_i^2=kp(1-p)+k^2p^2,\] where \(\bar{X}\) is the sample mean. Sloving for \(k\) and \(p\) leads to \[\hat{k}=\frac{\bar{X}^2}{\bar{X}-(1/n)\Sigma_{i=1}^{n}(X_i-\bar{X})^2}~~ and ~~\hat{p}=\frac{\bar{X}}{\hat{k}}\] It is difficult to analyze the performance of \(\hat{k}\) and \(\hat{p}\) analytically so you are asked to perform a simulation study using R. The idea is to generate random samples and investigate the performance of \(\hat{k}\) and \(\hat{p}\) using random samples.

Question 1

Generate a single simple random sample of length n <- 50 from the binomial distribution with the parameters k <- 10, p <- 0.4 (1 point).

k = 10
p = 0.4
n = 50
sample = rbinom(n,k,p)
sample
##  [1] 4 4 5 2 3 6 6 5 4 2 5 7 5 2 6 8 2 6 7 6 5 6 4 3 4 4 1 4 4 5 2 5 3 2 5 2 5 6
## [39] 2 3 3 3 1 3 6 3 1 6 3 6

Question 2

Write a function that takes a sample as its input and returns a vector containing the estimates of k and p given above (3 points).

estimators = function(x){
  x_bar = mean(x)
  sum_square = 1/length(x) * sum(x^2)
  k_hat = x_bar^2 / (x_bar - (sum_square - x_bar^2))
  p_hat = x_bar / k_hat
  result = c(k_hat, p_hat)
  names(result) = c("k_hat", "p_hat")
  result
}
estimators(sample)
##      k_hat      p_hat 
## 15.4220183  0.2658537

Question 3

Generate N <- 1000 samples of size n <- 50 (as in the first question) and calculate N <- 1000 estimates of \(k\) and N <- 1000 estimates of \(p\) (4 points if no loops are used in the code, 2 points if any loop (for, while, repeat, etc.) is used in the code ).

N <- 1000
simulation = replicate(N, rbinom(n, k, p), FALSE)
result = lapply(simulation, estimators)
df50 = data.frame(matrix(unlist(result), nrow=length(result), byrow=TRUE))

Question 5

Estimate the bias and the mean squared error (MSE) of \(\hat{k}\) and the bias and the MSE of \(\hat{p}\) for each sample size (n <- 50, n <- 100 and n <- 250). Do the estimators seem to overestimate or underestimate the parameters? How do the bias and the MSE change when the sample size increases? (3 points).

# MSE for n = 50 and k hat
mse_50_k = sum((df50$k_hat - mean(df50$k_hat))^2)/N
# MSE for n = 100 and k hat
mse_100_k = sum((df100$k_hat - mean(df100$k_hat))^2)/N
# MSE for n = 250 and k hat
mse_250_k = sum((df250$k_hat - mean(df250$k_hat))^2)/N

# MSE for n = 50 and p hat
mse_50_p = sum((df50$p_hat - mean(df50$p_hat))^2)/N
# MSE for n = 100 and p hat
mse_100_p = sum((df100$p_hat - mean(df100$p_hat))^2)/N
# MSE for n = 250 and p hat
mse_250_p = sum((df250$p_hat - mean(df250$p_hat))^2)/N

# bias for n = 50 and k hat
bias_50_k = mean(df50$k_hat) - k
# bias for n = 100 and k hat
bias_100_k = mean(df100$k_hat) - k
# bias for n = 250 and k hat
bias_250_k = mean(df250$k_hat) - k

# bias for n = 50 and p hat
bias_50_p = mean(df50$p_hat) - p
# bias for n = 100 and p hat
bias_100_p = mean(df100$p_hat) - p
# bias for n = 250 and p hat
bias_250_p = mean(df250$p_hat) - p

# Table for MSE's
mse_matrix = matrix(c(mse_50_k, mse_100_k, mse_250_k,
                      mse_50_p, mse_100_p, mse_250_p), byrow = TRUE, nrow = 2)
colnames(mse_matrix) = c("n = 50", "n = 100", "n = 250")
rownames(mse_matrix) = c("k hat", "p hat")
kable(mse_matrix, caption = "Table for MSE's")

Since the biases are positive, our estimators \(\hat{k}\) and \(\hat{p}\) overestimate the parameters \(k\) and \(p\). Moreover, as the sample size \(n\) increases, our MSE and bias of estimators \(\hat{k}\) and \(\hat{p}\) decreases.

  1. Make a single plot using ggplot2 that contains three box plots of the estimates of the parameter k when n <- 50, n <- 100, n <- 250 (the first from the left box plot has to describe the estimates when n <- 50, the second from the left box plot has to describe the estimates when n <- 100 and the third from the left box plot has to describe the estimates n <- 250). Include the true value of the parameter as a horizontal line (geom_hline() and use the argument color) and label the plot appropriately (4 points).
size = rep(c('50', '100', '250'), each = 1000)
q6df = rbind(df50, df100, df250)
q6df = data.frame(size, q6df)
ggplot(data = q6df, mapping = aes(x = reorder(size, -k_hat), y = k_hat, col = size)) + 
  geom_boxplot() + 
  geom_hline(aes(yintercept = 10)) + 
  ggtitle("Boxplot for estimated k by size") +
  labs(y = "Estimated k", x = "Sample size")

# Extra credit - using basic R function
q6df$size = factor(q6df$size , levels=c('50', '100', '250'))
boxplot(k_hat ~ size, q6df,
        xlab = "Sample size", ylab = "Estimated k",
        main = "Boxplot for estimated k by size",
        col = c("blue", "red", "green"),
        outcol = c("blue", "red", "green"))
legend("right", inset=.02, title="size",
   c("50","100","250"), fill=c("blue", "red", "green"), horiz=FALSE, cex=0.8)
abline(h=10)
